description: From Middle English voide, voyde, from Old French vuit, voide, vuide (modern vide), in turn from a Vulgar Latin *vocitus, related to Latin vacuus (“empty”).

entries.meaning: Containing nothing; empty; not occupied or filled.
examples: I'll chain him in my study, that, at void hours, / I may run over the story of his country.

entries.meaning: Having no incumbent; unoccupied; said of offices etc.
Being without; destitute; devoid.
examples: He that is void of wisdom despiseth his neighbor.

entries.meaning: Not producing any effect; ineffectual; vain.
examples: [My word] shall not return to me void, but it shall accomplish that which I please.

entries.meaning: Of no legal force or effect, incapable of confirmation or ratification.
Containing no immaterial quality; destitute of mind or soul.
(computing, programming, of a function or method) That does not return a value; a procedure.
An empty space; a vacuum.
examples: Nobody has crossed the void since one man died trying three hundred years ago; it's high time we had another go.

entries.meaning: (astronomy) An extended region of space containing no galaxies.
(materials science) A collection of adjacent vacancies inside a crystal lattice.
(fluid mechanics) A pocket of vapour inside a fluid flow, created by cavitation.
(construction) An empty space between floors or walls, including false separations and planned gaps between a building and its facade.
(Internet, humorous) A black cat.
examples: My little void is so sweet sometimes.

entries.meaning: An empty place; A location that has nothing useful.

verbs.description: void (third-person singular simple present voids, present participle voiding, simple past and past participle voided)

entries.meaning: (transitive) To make invalid or worthless.
examples: He voided the check and returned it.

entries.meaning: (transitive, medicine) To empty.
To throw or send out; to evacuate; to emit; to discharge.
(intransitive, obsolete) To withdraw, depart.
(transitive, obsolete) To remove the contents of; to make or leave vacant or empty; to quit; to leave.
(now rare, historical) A voidee. [from 15th c.]
examples: Late on the final evening, as the customary ‘void’ – spiced wine and sweetmeats – was served, more elaborate disguisings in the great hall culminated in the release of a flock of white doves.
